WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Hello, Sarah and I are statisticians working in the UK Government.

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:07.000
We lead on the development of the ShinyGovStyle R package

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:10.000
and we want to share a bit about our experience of how we've used it to help us

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:14.000
and others across the UK build production-ready RShiny apps.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.000
During the pandemic, we saw a huge surge in people wanting more data and wanting it now.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.000
With RShiny, we found we were able to build dashboards within hours

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:26.000
instead of requiring a full software engineering team that could have taken weeks or months to build.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Naturally, as all these dashboards were then appearing,

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:33.000
we then got a lot of pressure to be able to publish these as fast as we were making them.

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:36.000
So, we ended up in this position.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:41.000
Statisticians standing there, fresh RShiny app in hand, knocking on the door of our IT teams.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
At this point, we found lots of red tape and just generally we were lost in a world

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.000
quite far outside of our comfort zone as R developers.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
We quickly realised we're not as irresistible as puss in boots,

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:56.000
so we had to take a different approach.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:59.000
That's where we picked up the development of the Shiny GovStyle package.

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:05.000
We've used this to pull in the UK government design system into RShiny itself.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.000
There are three main challenges we want to talk about today.

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.000
The first one is accessibility.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:14.000
We want to make sure our apps work for all users and work for assistive technologies

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.000
such as voice activation and screen readers.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Trustworthiness.

00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
This is all about getting our IT teams to trust that we can build reliable apps

00:01:23.000 --> 00:01:26.000
and getting our end users to trust the apps that we publish as well.

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Last but not least, as package developers, we've been battling with usefulness.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Ensuring that we can maximise the value from the time we spend on the package

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:39.000
and also understand our role in the wider government development landscape as well.

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:46.000
For accessibility, in the UK, all public sector services must follow

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:49.000
the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines, or WCAG for short.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:52.000
As our developers, we've had to show that we understand

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.000
how to develop accessible web applications.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:57.000
Otherwise, we're simply not allowed to publish.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:02.000
First thing, we found that we weren't really aware of the range or prevalence

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:04.000
of accessibility needs out there.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:08.000
Like many people, we often tested our dashboards ourselves

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:09.000
and then thought, that was that.

00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:11.000
If it works for me, it's going to work for everyone else.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:13.000
This was quite a big blind spot.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:17.000
I've got a few stats from the World Health Organisation and other bodies

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:19.000
just to illustrate the prevalence a little bit more.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:23.000
If you imagine you're in an average room of 10 adults,

00:02:24.000 --> 00:02:27.000
8 out of 10 people in that room will have a vision impairment.

00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.000
This could be full blindness, low or poor vision,

00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:33.000
or other conditions such as cataracts.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:37.000
3 out of 10 people in that room will have some form of dexterity impairment.

00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:41.000
So, fine motor skills and hand-eye coordination will be affected.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Another 3 people in that room will only ever access the internet

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:47.000
using their phone.

00:02:48.000 --> 00:02:50.000
These numbers are huge portions of the population

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:53.000
and not all of them will use your Shiny app.

00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.000
But if you're publishing publicly or you work in an organisation

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:58.000
of hundreds or even thousands of users,

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:01.000
it's far more likely than you think that these users will need to use

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:02.000
your Shiny app.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:05.000
I just want to take a step back for a second

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:06.000
and ask a very simple question.

00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:08.000
How do you brush your teeth?

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:13.000
In the UK, over 2 in 3 adults now use an electric toothbrush.

00:03:13.000 --> 00:03:15.000
And even if you don't use one personally,

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:16.000
you can see why they would.

00:03:16.000 --> 00:03:18.000
They help you do more but with less effort.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:20.000
So, what's not to like?

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:23.000
They were originally invented in 1927

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:25.000
just to assist people with limited motor skills

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:26.000
so they could brush their teeth.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
And it wasn't until the 60s that manufacturers developed

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:31.000
more mainstream models and later on

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:33.000
as they gradually gained popularity.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:35.000
And I find this is a really nice example

00:03:35.000 --> 00:03:39.000
of just how designing something with accessibility in mind

00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:42.000
to make a fairly common everyday task easier

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:44.000
has actually made it easier for everyone else

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:45.000
in the population as well.

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:48.000
So, hopefully it shows,

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:50.000
even if you were watching that earlier bit

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:53.000
and thought, not enough people use my Shiny app,

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:54.000
don't need to worry about this.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Actually, all you're doing there is cheating yourself

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
of the benefits of designing with accessibility in mind.

00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:04.000
So, I've got a really simple example here

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:06.000
of the difference that styling and colours can make.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:09.000
So, this first clip, I'm going to demo a very basic Shiny app

00:04:09.000 --> 00:04:10.000
with no additional styling.

00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:12.000
And I want you to see,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:15.000
can you see what part of the dropdown a user is focused on?

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.000
At first, with a cursor, you can kind of look across

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:20.000
and see where the cursor is in relation to the dropdown.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:22.000
If I navigate with a keyboard now,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:25.000
can you still follow where the user is focusing?

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:28.000
I have fairly good vision.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:30.000
I am still struggling just at a small distance from a screen

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:31.000
to see where this is.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
It's a very light green, grey shading there.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:36.000
So, this is a dropdown that's just got three options.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:38.000
But imagine if you had 33 options,

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:40.000
how easily you could lose your place and where you are.

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:43.000
That's a huge difference.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
So, within our package, we've added our own functions

00:04:49.000 --> 00:04:52.000
and we add in the standard styling that has high contrast.

00:04:52.000 --> 00:04:54.000
So, if I play this next example,

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:56.000
you can see how much clearer it is

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.000
to spot where the user is focusing

00:04:58.000 --> 00:04:59.000
at any given point in time.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.000
And having a strong contrast for interactive elements like this

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:05.000
or text is hugely important.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
As a simple rule, you generally want to aim

00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:09.000
for at least a 3 to 1 contrast ratio.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And I've got a QR code and link here

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:13.000
if you want to go and check off your own styling

00:05:13.000 --> 00:05:15.000
because not everyone's going to want to use

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:16.000
the UK government branding.

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:18.000
You'll all have your own themes and branding yourselves

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:19.000
and organizations.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
So, you can go off, you can check your own colors

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:24.000
and just make sure you have enough contrast

00:05:24.000 --> 00:05:25.000
in places like this.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.000
Next, I want to give you a bit of a flavor

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:31.000
of what it's like for a screen reader user

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:32.000
when they interact with a website.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:36.000
So, for this one, I want you to think about

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:37.000
what this site is for.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:39.000
Can you tell what this site is for

00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:40.000
just from what the screen reader tells you?

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Nice and clear, right?

00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:09.000
This is what the app itself looks like.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:13.000
One of the first things that was a problem here

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:14.000
is there was no title set.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:17.000
So, it just read out the raw URL to start with.

00:06:17.000 --> 00:06:19.000
So, immediately, you're lacking a bit of context.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:21.000
As you went through the navigation links,

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:23.000
you said, click here, click here, click here.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:25.000
You couldn't really tell what they were going for,

00:06:25.000 --> 00:06:26.000
where they'd take you to.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:28.000
There were some icons in there

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:29.000
that might have given you clues,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.000
but they're not all obviously linked or clear.

00:06:33.000 --> 00:06:35.000
As it came down the page, there was no heading.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:37.000
So, you just went straight to the image.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:42.000
And also, with the image, it had alt text in,

00:06:42.000 --> 00:06:44.000
but that alt text, all it did was tell you

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:46.000
it was an image with information.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:47.000
So, it just teased you.

00:06:47.000 --> 00:06:50.000
And really, that might as well have not been there at all.

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
You just couldn't get any of this information from that.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:55.000
I've got another app now

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
which uses our ShinyGov style package,

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.000
and I want you to see if from the screen reader readout

00:07:01.000 --> 00:07:03.000
you can actually understand where you are in the app.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:06.000
Mount Cars Explorer homepage document.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.000
Visited link skipped to main content.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:11.000
Main landmark heading level one homepage.

00:07:11.000 --> 00:07:14.000
This website allows you to explore the Cars dataset,

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
comparing car models directly,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:19.000
finding statistics by car characteristics

00:07:19.000 --> 00:07:21.000
and plotting variables against each other.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.000
Contents list with four items.

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:27.000
Compare characteristics. Visited link.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:29.000
Charts. Visited link.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:31.000
Tables. Visited link.

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:33.000
Homepage. Visited link.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:38.000
Yes.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:39.000
So, both of these examples

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:41.000
have the screen reader set fairly slow

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:42.000
for the user to understand.

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:45.000
First thing I think you'll notice with this one

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:46.000
is there was a clear title marked.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:49.000
Admittedly, it struggled a little bit with empty cars.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.000
I think they called it Mount Cars instead.

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:53.000
But it gives you a little bit of context straightaway

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:55.000
as to where you are, what the page is that you're on.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:07:58.000
As we went down, there was a skip to main content link

00:07:58.000 --> 00:07:59.000
which I'll show you in the next slide

00:07:59.000 --> 00:08:01.000
when we see what the website looked like.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:03.000
That allowed me with a keyboard

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:04.000
just to jump to the main content,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:06.000
get straight to the text,

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:07.000
explaining what the website was.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
Next, I then reverse tabbed back into the navigation links.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:13.000
As soon as you went into them, you could hear

00:08:13.000 --> 00:08:15.000
you were in a contents list.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:16.000
There were four links there.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:17.000
And each of the links told me

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:18.000
what I'd be tabbing into,

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:21.000
whether that was the charts or the tables

00:08:21.000 --> 00:08:22.000
or anything like that.

00:08:24.000 --> 00:08:26.000
So, as a user, hopefully you can see now

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
how big of a difference you can make

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.000
to someone who's using a screen reader.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:34.000
This is what that app looked like.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:36.000
I'm just going to press play here

00:08:36.000 --> 00:08:38.000
so you can see the skip link itself.

00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:40.000
You might have seen these on other websites.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.000
And they're really, really helpful for keyboard users.

00:08:42.000 --> 00:08:45.000
If you try and navigate just using your keyboard,

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:47.000
you'll soon start to see a lot of websites

00:08:47.000 --> 00:08:50.000
have a lot of links and various stuff

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:52.000
near the top of navigation

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.000
that is usually helpful just to skip straight to the content.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:00.000
And also on this, it's just a little bit cleaner,

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:01.000
a little bit clearer.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:03.000
Even looking at it, you've got clear content.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:05.000
You can see the text cleanly.

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:06.000
There's that title across the top.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:08.000
You know what you're looking at.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
On this slide, I've got a screenshot from NVDA,

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:14.000
non-visual desktop access,

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:16.000
which is the free screen reader I was using

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:17.000
for the last couple of examples.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:20.000
And you can see how the first layout of this,

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:22.000
only the links are listed.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:23.000
And that's because it's quite common for users

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:26.000
just to navigate through a site using the links alone.

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
If you think back to the first example

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:29.000
and you heard the content read out,

00:09:29.000 --> 00:09:30.000
all the links were saying,

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.000
click here, click here, click here.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.000
There had no real context to what they were doing.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:37.000
And for users using assistive technology like this,

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:38.000
this has a massive impact

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
because of the way they tend to try and navigate about.

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:42.000
So imagine this screenshot,

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:45.000
but it just said, click here, all the way through.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:46.000
How on earth would you know

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:48.000
where you were and what the structure of the site was

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:50.000
to be able to navigate it?

00:09:50.000 --> 00:09:51.000
In practice, you probably wouldn't,

00:09:51.000 --> 00:09:52.000
and you'd just give up.

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:56.000
And this is one of the things that we've done

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.000
within the package.

00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:00.000
So to tackle this issue,

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.000
we've built our own external link function.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
So we've made sure that for developers themselves,

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:07.000
this function's pretty much the same

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:11.000
as just using the tags from Shiny or HTML tools.

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
You put your href in, you put your link text in.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:15.000
But behind the scenes, we do some accessibility checks

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.000
to help link text be a bit more useful.

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
So the first thing we've done is curated our own list

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
or data set within the package

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
of bad and non-descriptive link text.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:28.000
Examples like click here are the common ones.

00:10:28.000 --> 00:10:30.000
And if that's matched within the link text argument,

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:31.000
we just give an error

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
and tell the developer to be more descriptive.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:34.000
We also give a warning

00:10:34.000 --> 00:10:37.000
if link text is less than seven characters long

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
because one-word links are less descriptive generally.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:42.000
Plus, for users with mobility impairments,

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:44.000
single words are actually quite hard to click on.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:46.000
They're not a very big target area.

00:10:46.000 --> 00:10:48.000
And last but not least in this,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.000
we've also added a hidden screen reader message

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:52.000
that's not visual on the site all the time.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
It's an option to toggle that.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:56.000
But behind the scenes, it'll just add opens in a new tab

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.000
for any external links that take you to a different site.

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:00.000
Even as a visual user,

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
opening a new tab can be quite disorientating sometimes.

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
But if you're using a screen reader,

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
you can't see you're suddenly in a new tab

00:11:07.000 --> 00:11:09.000
when you browse on a completely different site.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:11.000
So this makes a huge impact just warning them

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
that that's what's going to happen.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:15.000
It's a very simple function

00:11:15.000 --> 00:11:17.000
in the small part of the package that we've done,

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:18.000
but it's a really nice example

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
of how we've been able to pull together

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
our knowledge that we've built up through this process

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:24.000
and put those into easy-to-use functions

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
to allow other developers

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
to build their shiny apps just as quickly

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:30.000
but with nice guardrails around them

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:32.000
to help keep them accessible.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:35.000
So now I'm going to pass over to Sarah for the next section.

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:38.000
In an age where most people have access to the internet

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.000
and there are swathes of information out there,

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:42.000
how do they know what to trust?

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And similarly, at a time where the information we release

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
is heavily scrutinized

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
and new cuts of data are requested frequently,

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.000
how can we convince our digital and IT colleagues

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:54.000
to let us publish shiny apps that statisticians have created

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:57.000
when a great deal of risk is involved?

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.000
To illustrate this issue,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
which of these would you trust?

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
On the left hand here, we've got this cat facts website

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:08.000
which may or may not send you some spam text messages,

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:09.000
and on the right hand side,

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
we've got the National Geographic page

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:14.000
which clearly lists out some facts about cats.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:15.000
The stakes here are clearly lower

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
when we're trying to find out cat facts,

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:18.000
but for the general public,

00:12:18.000 --> 00:12:20.000
how do they know what they can trust

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:23.000
for schools, the economy or the environment?

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
People are aware of misinformation on the web

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
but we need to make it clear to our users

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.000
that our statistics are trustworthy

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.000
and can be relied upon.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
We also need to closely work with security and IT experts

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:37.000
in our departments to clear any external outputs,

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:38.000
but how can we get their buy-in

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:40.000
if our pages look more like catfacts.org

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:43.000
and less like National Geographic?

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:46.000
This is where gov.uk design comes in.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:48.000
The simple and clean design of gov.uk

00:12:48.000 --> 00:12:50.000
gives users trust in our outputs

00:12:50.000 --> 00:12:52.000
and presents them with a familiar layout.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.000
The design's been really extensively tested

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
and developed with user researchers,

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.000
making sure that it works for users

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
with all different types of accessibility needs.

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:04.000
And this CSS is published online for developers to use

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:07.000
on the gov.uk design system website.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
It's helpfully split out into components

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
like you can see with the button here.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:14.000
It tells developers when they should use the component,

00:13:14.000 --> 00:13:18.000
how it works, and has links to the underlying HTML.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
We can then use this CSS file,

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:22.000
make some minor tweaks,

00:13:22.000 --> 00:13:25.000
and then use the attached dependencies call

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:28.000
from HTML tools to attach this static CSS styling

00:13:28.000 --> 00:13:31.000
to our shiny widgets in shiny-gov-style.

00:13:32.000 --> 00:13:33.000
To demonstrate the impact of this,

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
take a look at an app with and without

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:38.000
the shiny-gov-style styling attached.

00:13:38.000 --> 00:13:40.000
So this is our showcase example app

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
and you can see that without the shiny-gov-style styling,

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.000
the radio buttons are stacked on top of each other,

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
we've got quite messy contents,

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
and the cookies and the header bar

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:50.000
all look quite cluttered.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
As soon as we've attached the CSS styling

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
with that attached dependencies call,

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:59.000
this neatens it up and brings it into the gov.uk design.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:02.000
This results in a page that's powered by shiny

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:05.000
but looks and feels like a real gov.uk page.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:07.000
So on the left here in this example,

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.000
I've got a real gov.uk service

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
and this is civil service jobs.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:12.000
And on the right hand side,

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:15.000
I've mocked this up using our shiny-gov-style package.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.000
You'll see the design elements are really similar

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
from the heading bars and the cookies

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:22.000
to the beta banner and the email and password entry.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:25.000
And there's a really clear link to accessibility here.

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:28.000
So being able to navigate pages with a similar layout,

00:14:28.000 --> 00:14:29.000
it's really important for those

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
who can't visually see a screen.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
Like we saw in Cam's demo earlier,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
it does take a while to orient yourself

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
in a new and unfamiliar page layout.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:40.000
So using the gov.uk layout benefits both users

00:14:40.000 --> 00:14:43.000
with accessibility needs and those without.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
And this clear similarity helps us gain trust

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
with our stakeholders who we need to convince

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.000
to let us release information this way

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:53.000
and our users who need to be able to rely on our outputs.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
IT and digital know that the elements in the page

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
meet accessibility guidelines,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:58.000
although they'll still need to check this

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:00.000
on a case-by-case basis to make sure

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
that analysts are using these appropriately.

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:04.000
And users of apps,

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
whether they can visually see the page or not

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.000
will be familiar with this design,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.000
building trust in our outputs.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:12.000
The last barrier that we faced

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:13.000
was something that might be familiar

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:15.000
to all package developers,

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
and that is usefulness.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:20.000
So how do we keep the package useful to our users

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
without making unnecessary work for ourselves?

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.000
Our package is developed and maintained

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:26.000
by a team of volunteers

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:28.000
across lots of different departments

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
in UK sort of service.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
So utilizing their resource effectively

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:33.000
is really important.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:35.000
Our GitHub issue log helps us keep on top

00:15:35.000 --> 00:15:37.000
of what users are asking for,

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:38.000
what bugs have been raised,

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:41.000
and which volunteer is working on it.

00:15:41.000 --> 00:15:43.000
One example of a useful feature

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:45.000
that we've recently added to the package

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:47.000
is styled reactable tables

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:50.000
to something that a user had requested.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:51.000
So out of the box,

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:54.000
these aren't always suitable for GitHub.UK dashboards.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:55.000
You might be able to see

00:15:55.000 --> 00:15:57.000
there's a very small sorting arrow

00:15:57.000 --> 00:15:59.000
that appears at the top,

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.000
but these are really hard to make out

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:03.000
with visual impairments.

00:16:03.000 --> 00:16:04.000
We decided it was worth our time

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:06.000
to add new CSS for reactables

00:16:06.000 --> 00:16:08.000
to the standard Gov.UK design

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:10.000
as it is a fairly niche use

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
for analysts building R Shiny dashboards

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:16.000
and unlikely to have any replication across government.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:29.000
The result of this is a Gov-styled reactable table.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:30.000
So we took a lot of elements

00:16:30.000 --> 00:16:33.000
from the current static table in the top left,

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:36.000
which was designed on the Gov.UK design system.

00:16:36.000 --> 00:16:38.000
So we don't want to diverge too far

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:40.000
from this user research design,

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:43.000
and we want to keep that trust with our users.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:46.000
So this simply adds in things like accessible sorting

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:48.000
with the blue bars you can see

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
at the top and the bottom of the column headers

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:54.000
and accessible hover overs with that yellow highlight

00:16:54.000 --> 00:16:58.000
so that it's really clear what a user is focusing on.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:06.000
An example of an issue

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:09.000
that we decided not to fix is dark mode.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:12.000
So this is a much wider government issue,

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.000
and it's been raised with the design team for many years.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:17.000
They've been looking at tackling it in the long run,

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:19.000
and we don't just want to spin up a version of it

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:20.000
that analysts will come to use,

00:17:20.000 --> 00:17:22.000
which we then need to change to fit

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:25.000
with wider government branding later on.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:27.000
So building 50 different versions of dark mode

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
can make it really hard to keep that trust with users

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.000
that we mentioned earlier across all services.

00:17:33.000 --> 00:17:36.000
Dark mode's been an ongoing conversation since 2018.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:39.000
You can see when this person raised it.

00:17:39.000 --> 00:17:42.000
And in GovDesign, there are a lot of changes involved

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:44.000
that are much bigger than our little package

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:48.000
with a fairly small use case for analytical dashboards.

00:17:48.000 --> 00:17:50.000
This thread shows a lot of people going off

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:51.000
and building their own versions,

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:53.000
each different from each other,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:55.000
and we don't want to be adding to this list of things

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:58.000
to consolidate once a fix is finally in.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:17:59.000
So there's a real challenge here

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
in deciding where best to spend our time

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:04.000
as package developers to add the most value.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:06.000
And the solution's been working really closely

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
with both of our users and the wider government

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:11.000
to understand how the package is being used

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:14.000
and when wider changes might affect it.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:16.000
Thanks to ShinyGovStyle,

00:18:16.000 --> 00:18:17.000
analysts all the way across government

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:20.000
have now been able to easily publish dashboards

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:23.000
for both external and internal use.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.000
The package has lowered the barrier for entry

00:18:24.000 --> 00:18:27.000
to publishing dashboards for many analysts,

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.000
and it's now used in a range of departments

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:32.000
from education and tax, where Cam and I work,

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.000
to health and the environment.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.000
So no more begging our IT colleagues

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:38.000
to let us publish these dashboards

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:40.000
thanks to ShinyGovStyle.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:42.000
The package continues to be maintained

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
by a team of volunteers across government

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:46.000
who are all really passionate about making sure

00:18:46.000 --> 00:18:50.000
that our apps and services are accessible to everybody.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
If you want to find out more

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:54.000
or have a little poke around our package,

00:18:54.000 --> 00:18:56.000
please scan this QR code,

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
which will take us to the documentation

00:18:58.000 --> 00:18:59.000
for ShinyGovStyle.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:02.000
From there, that links out to our source code on GitHub,

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:05.000
and you can contact either me or Cam through there too.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:07.000
Thanks for your time today.

